\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \b\fs28\lang2057 {\fs24 <#/>The ruling par
ty, Kanu, and five of its top officials yesterday scoffed at a Sh39 million suit filed against them, calling it "purely <-/imaginatory>, speculative and based on greed".
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\fs24 <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 "The suit as filed is bad in law, frivolous and vexatious and discloses no reasona
ble cause of action against the defendants either in their personal capacity as principal office bearers of Kanu or on their capacity," the defendants said in a replying defence statement.
\par <#/>The officials have denied owing Nyanja Architects and Company Sh39. 6 million for alleged breach of contract. They want the suit summarily struck out with costs.
\par <#/>The replying statement was filed in the High Court by lawyer Mutula Kilonzo.
\par <#/>In a separate defence statement, Mr David Pius Mugambi, the party's national Executive Officer, denied contracting Nyanja for a Kenyatta International Conference Centre project.
\par <#/>He had no powers to commit Kanu and its members in the manner alleged in the suit's plaint, he claimed.
\par <#/>Nyanja filed the suit on May 29 naming
 the Kanu national Chairman, Mr Peter Oloo Aringo, the Secretary General, Mr Joseph Kamotho, the Treasurer, Mr Japheth Lijoodi, the Organising Secretary, Mr Stephen Kalonzo Musyoka and Mr Mugambi as the defendants.
\par <#/>Nyanja is represented by Waruhiu and Muite Advocates and is seeking general damages, total payment of fees plus interest at 19 per cent in addition to the cost of the suit.
\par <#/>The firm claims that the party owes it Sh39,652,907 for work done and/or professional services rendered. <#/>This co
nsists of "preparation of drawings and specifications for the duration of the erection of the rehabilitation of the defendants' premises known as the Kenyatta International Conference Centre (KICC)".
\par <#/>Nyanja's plaint claims that Kanu should have paid him by April 4.
\par <#/>In a common defence statement, four of the party officials, who are also sitting MPs, said they were wrongfully sued and that the procedure employed in the commencement of the suit was a direct abuse of the process of the court.
\par <#/>They said the suit was calculated to scandalise them, Kanu and its members in general.
\par <#/>The four denied owing the Nyanja firm Sh39,652,907 for work or professional service allegedly done and rendered. <#/>They challenged the architectural firm to prove its claims beyond reasonable doubt.
\par <#/>At no time, they said, did Nyanja and Company prepare any outline, proposals, scheme, design or any acceptable production drawings for the erection of the KICC.
\par <#/>They challenged Mr George Nyanja, the firm's proprietor, to adduce evidence to show that the alleged 39. 6 was due to be payable to the plaintiff by April 4 or at any other time at an interest rate of 19 per cent.
\par <#/>They claimed that the company's claim that it was appointed by Mr Mugambi was absolutely }{\i\fs24\lang2057 ultra vires}{\fs24\lang2057  the powers vested in the officer who wrote and signed the alleged letter.
\par <#/>The alleged appointment letter, they say, was always an offer to treat and did not create any enforceable or <-/privity> of the contract before actual service <-_were><+_was> rendered.
\par <#/>"It was not followed by any service under the Architects and Quantity/Surveyors Act or Conditions of Engagement, therein provided, or at all to warrant fees," they said.
\par <#/>The approval by Kanu's executive committee and the City Commission, who are the final signatories of such contracts, were never obtained.
\par <#/>They also charged that Mr Nyanja, himself a member of Kanu, should always have known the party's contracting procedures. <#/>"These were not followed," their joint statement said.
\par <#/>By February 21, their statement said (without any prejudice), the work had been "abandoned".
\par <#/>"Accordingly, the figure of Sh39,562,907 }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>different amount}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 is purely imaginary, based on greed, has no basis and is not due," they said.
\par <#/>In his separate defence, Mr Mugambi said the letter of April 11, 1990, was written at Mr Nyanja's instigation, who at the time was processing his application for re-admission to Kanu following his suspension from the party.
\par <#/>The agreement, Mr Mugambi told the court, was at the time meant to be free and at no cost or at most under conditions of engagement and scale of professional charges for architects.
\par <#/>The letter was also intended to enable the plaintiff to start the compilation of a suitable list of consultants for scrutiny and confirmation by Kanu and its executive organs.
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>He said that following the writing of the letter, Nyanja never acknowledged acceptance until after the cancellation of a letter dated February 19.
\par <#/>He says that the proposed relationship was terminated by the letter of February 19.
\par <#/>The five Kanu officials were directed on May 30 by Mr Justice Norbury Dugdale to appear in court and defend the party against the claims.
\par <#/>Mr Justice Dugdale, at the same time, directed Nyanja to serve summonses on the officials individually and personally and not through newspaper notices.
\par <#/>The judge made the orders when the case was brought before his}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057  ex-parte}{\v\fs24\lang2057  regarding the mode of service to the officials.
\par }\pard\plain \s46\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v <#/>Nyanja also claims that by a letter of February 21, signed by Mr Mugambi, the defendants purported to terminate the company's appointment as Kanu's architects for the project wit
hout giving it an opportunity to be heard.}{</X>
