\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <I> <h> <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Why we're ready to go to jail - Muite}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Lawyer Paul Muite and his co-defendants in the LSK contempt suit wound up their case yesterday and accused the Government of manipulating courts through proxies to silence its critics.
\par <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Making his final submissions, Mr Muite charged that the Government was determined to imprison the current LSK council members because of their stand for democracy and justice in the country.
\par <#/>Later in the afternoon, there was a brief drama in court when a lawyer, Ms Martha Njoka, was ordered out after she defied the judge's directive to stop talking while another lawyer was addressing the court.
\par <#/>Mr Justice John Mwera said: "May you keep quiet. <#/>And, may you please change position and stop talking or you walk out," to which Ms Njoka responded: "My lord, I'm not going to change position. <#/><-_I'll><+_I'd> rather walk out."
\par <#/>She was not able to attend most of the afternoon session, during which Mr A. B Shah (counsel for the four lawyers who instigated the proceedings against Mr Muite and his council) was making his final submissions.
\par <#/>During the morning session, Mr Muite told the packed gallery: "If our going to pri
son will hasten the day when Kenya can have a truly free and independent Judiciary, hasten the day when the Kenyan people can freely elect their leaders, and if our going to prison will assist in the achievement of meaningful and peaceful reforms, the LSK
 council considers their imprisonment a small price to pay to avoid the bloodshed, loss of life and suffering which will inevitably be paid.
\par <#/>"Our prayer is that by the time we come out of prison, the reforms Kenyans need so urgently will have been realised. <#/>It is bad governance that poses}{\b\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_article>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 
greatest danger to true public security and }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_article>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 
future of this nation and not the LSK. <#/>Our faith while in prison will be the knowledge that the present leadership will not, and cannot, stop t
he tide. <#/>Sooner or later, changes will come. <#/>We have no doubt that it will be sooner (rather) than later. <#/>The LSK and its council will have played its part and paid its share of the sacrifice."
\par <#/>The lawyer clashed and differed <_/severally> with the judge when he tried to refer to an article by lawyer Gitobu Imanyara published in the }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Nairobi Law Monthly}{\fs24\lang2057  magazine.
\par <#/>The article says, among other things, that the Government was committed to using unorthodox ways to silence its critics.
\par <#/>Mr Justice Mwera warned Mr Muite that he would not condone any political references because they were irrelevant to the proceedings.
\par <#/>Mr Muite insisted that as a defendant in a public trial he was entitled to refer to anything suitable for his defence. <#/>But Mr Justice Mwera told him the proceedings were chamber matters and not public.
\par <#/>Reading from a 14-page submission signed by all the defendants, Mr Muite said that the committal proceedings against them were an abuse of the process of court, and, therefore, "a not-too-subtle attempt by the Government to silence its critics.
\par }\pard\plain \s46\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>He went on: "We have submitted, we have maintained, and we shall maintain that the sending of the LSK council members to jail would not in any way be a solution to the massiv
e problems currently facing the Government."
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Mr Muite the judge <O/> that the law and the courts would lose reputation }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>idiom}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 
miserably if the defendants were sent to prison.
\par <#/>He said it was the business of the LSK and its individual members to t
alk on "human rights violations, the rule of law, the overconcentration of power in the presidency, the emasculation of Parliament, the emasculation of Judiciary, the emasculation of the only party, Kanu, and the subordination of all other institutions to
 the presidency. <#/>This is what constitutional law is all about.
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>Talking in a hoarse voice and looking blankly at the judge, the lawyer said that the balance
\par <#/>of power envisaged in the 1963 Constitution was intended to guard against dictatorship and totalitarianism.
\par <#/>"This is exactly what has happened with the emasculation of all major institutions save, perhaps, the LSK, which would explain the present efforts by the Government, through its four proxies in this suit, to similarly emasculate the 
LSK," said Mr Muite.
\par <#/>The four lawyers are Mr Aaron Ringera, Mr Philip Kandie, Ms Nancy Baraza and Mr Nesbitt Onyango Ojwang.
\par <#/>Mr Muite's co-accused are his vice-chairman, Mr Willy Mutunga, Mr Japheth Shamalla, Mr Charles Nyachae, Ms Matrha Njoka, Mr F. Kagwe and Mr G. B. M Kariuki.
\par <#/>Mr Muite stressed that no court order could legitimately stop the LSK or any Kenyans from pointing out evils.
\par <#/>"Politics is when an individual declares his intention to contest elections in a particular constituency. <#/>The LSK has not asked to be elected to Parliament. <#/>Speaking about good governance is the right of every Kenyan," he said.
\par <#/>He said that stopping the governed from speaking about good governance was a crime against them and a violation of the constitution.
\par <#/>"This is perversion of justice. <#/>Let's not, therefore, <-/shadow box> in the present proceedings or indulge in pretences," he said.
\par <#/>He urged Mr Justice Mwera to seize the "golden opportunity to stem the tide against any further emasculation of the Judiciary by the Government by dismissing these contempt proceedings."
\par <#/>"Now is the opportunity for your lordship to do what is r
ight in law, in the eyes of the public and posterity. <#/>It is a great opportunity. <#/>Your lordship can do much good for our country. <#/>An <_/acquital> of the defendants in these proceedings will mark a major milestone towards freedom and democracy,"
 he said.
\par <#/>In the afternoon, Mr Shah, who is assisted by Mr Maxwell Ombogo, urged the court to jail the defendants for defying Mr Justice Joseph Mango and Mr Justice Norbury Dugdale's rulings.
\par <#/>Mr Shah will continue with his submissions next Friday when the proceedings resume.
\par <#/>The adjournment was granted after an application by Mr Muite that he was due to attend today's opening of the International Commission of Jurists' meeting at Naivasha.
\par <#/>Mr Shah also indicated he would be occupied with other court matters in Mombasa for two days early next week.}{\fs24\lang2057 </X>
