\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <I> <h> <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Moi angered by Shikuku attacks}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 President Moi yesterday criticised former Butere MP, Mr Martin Shikuku, for his continued attack of Government policies and agitation for change.
\par <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 In his Kiswahili speech during yesterday's Madaraka Day celebrations at Nairobi's Nyayo Stadium, President Moi said Mr Shikuku, who recently went to Kampala with other Kenyans for the African Lead
ership Forum Conference, had been "assigned to carry out certain plans in Kenya".
\par <#/>The President said Mr Shikuku's call for increases in producer prices will give rise to a corresponding increase in consumer prices "and with prices of food going up, it is the ordinary people who will suffer. <#/>We look on both sides of the matter".

\par <#/>"He says that he wants a licence to hold a rally; what will he tell you," President Moi asked, in reference to Mr Shikuku's application last week for a licence to hold a public rally at Nairobi's Uhuru Park on June 15.
\par <#/>President Moi said that he is aware of what those who were in Kampala recently were out to do in the country. <#/>He said that Mr Shikuku had three cars and a Mercedes and challenged him to say publicly 
"where he bought his three cars, among them a Mercedes".
\par <#/>Mr Shikuku and former Foreign Minister, Dr Munyua Waiyaki, the former secretary general of the Organisation of African Trade Union Unity (OATUU), Mr Dennis Akumu, academic and Non- Governmental O
rganisations (NGO) consultant, Dr Eddah Gachukia, artist, Mr Elimo Njau and university don, Dr Gichuki, were some of the Kenyans who attended the recently-concluded Leadership Forum in the Ugandan capital.
\par <#/>The President also accused Nairobi lawyer and publisher of the}{\i\fs24\lang2057  Nairobi Law Monthly}{\fs24\lang2057 
 magazine, Mr Gitobu Imanyara, of feigning sickness when he was recently arrested and charged with publishing a seditious leading article entitled }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Tribalism}{\fs24\lang2057 .
\par <#/>The President said he is a tolerant man but he has realise
d that the trickery of Africans is getting legendary and hit out at Mr Imanyara's lawyer (Dr John Khaminwa) for submitting that his client was "a dying man" and a doctor for saying that Mr Imanyara was "seriously ill".
\par <#/>President Moi hit out at those al
leging that Mr Imanyara was tortured and asked: "Who is doing this? When professionals start lying, that that one is seriously ill, that that one is a dying man, where are we going, where are we? Where is the future of our children?"
\par <#/>The President said "Europeans are still ignorant of African behaviour" and rushed to give Mr Imanyara a medal when Mr Imanyara had just "dashed out of his supposed death bed upon his release".
\par <#/>"You will judge for yourselves what kind of people these are who are getting medals," the President said in reference to Mr Imanyara's Golden Pen of Freedom prize awarded to him by the Paris-based International Federation of Newspaper Publishers.

\par <#/>President Moi criticised crusaders for change wondering what kind of change they were seeking to have in Kenya.
\par <#/>"We are a civilian government, do these people singing change, want us to have a military government? Do they want us to be like the 27 other African nations where there have been <foreign_>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 coup d'etat}{\fs24\lang2057 
s<foreign/>," the President asked.
\par <#/>President Moi said Kenya was "democratic, very democratic" and wondered why some people would want change imposed on the country. <#/>He said that though Kenyans had wanted queue-voting, he had scrapped it for the sake of peace but there 
were still some people still calling for change.
\par <#/>President Moi said advocates of change failed to see the chaos in neighbouring countries of Ethiopia, Sudan and Somalia. <#/>"Do you think that there will be peace when people are killing each other," the President posed.
\par <#/>The President said that during the Uganda peace talks in Nairobi in 1985, some of the warring factions had said that only a military solution would solve Uganda's problems, but still peace was elusive.
\par <#/>President Moi said peace in
 Ethiopia will come only as a result of reconciliation which will include all the parties involved in the conflict. <#/>Similarly, President Moi said, the reconstruction of Ethiopia must involve all the parties involved in the conflict, otherwise there wi
ll be no peace.
\par <#/>He said Kenya does not harbour Ugandans who want to fight their motherland and said that it was Uganda which was persistently attacking Kenya. <#/>President Moi said that Uganda is supported in his attacks on Kenya by "outside countries".
\par <#/>President Moi said that with the influx of refugees into the country, Kenyan security personnel will be on red alert and those out to subvert the peace will be locked up "to eat rice and grow fat".
\par <#/>"The police and all other security personnel are
 going to have a very busy time to ensure the security and protection of Kenyans. <#/>"We will not allow our peace to be disrupted. <#/>I am aware of many who want to wreck the peace in Kenya; I am fully aware," the President said.
\par <#/>He repeated his reversal of the order to ban the selling of second hand clothes in Kenya saying that the clothes are popular among the ordinary people and are worn also by some big people "including some who are seated behind me".
\par <#/>"There are some people who say that I jus
t stay at the State House and do not know what happens. <#/>No, I walk out like ordinary people and see for myself what Kenyans want and I say let second hand clothes be sold as long as this is done legally," President Moi said amid cheers.
\par <#/>President Moi said that soon, those hospitals which do not have drugs will be supplied with medicine. <#/>He said that }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_article>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 time has also come}{\b\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 
<&/>grammar}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 when doctors will be required to choose between serving in Government hospitals and going into private practice instead of having to work for the Government and at the same time run their own clinics.
\par <#/>He said that there are about 3,000 doctors in the country and the number will be going up every year as there will be 150 doctors graduating each year.
\par }\pard\plain \s46\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>
On civil servants, the President said that they must serve the people diligently and efficiently because that is their calling. <#/>He said that they should shun corruption and the tendency of files "disappearing" when Kenyans want to be served should sto
p.
