\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <I> <h> <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Moses Keino quits as House Speaker}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Mr Moses Kiprono arap Keino resigned yesterday as Speaker of the National Assembly, Kenya's supreme law-making institution.
\par <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 
In a statement he delivered to the Government-owned Kenya News Agency (KNA), Mr Keino did not give any reason for his resignation after three years and one month as Kenya's third Speaker. <#/>Before him were Mr Fredrick Gideon Mbithi Mati and the late Sir
 Humphrey Slade.
\par <#/>In the terse statement, the 53-year-old Keino thanked "most <-/heartedly>" the President and all Members of Parliament and staff for their cooperation and support during his tenure.
\par <#/>Sources told the}{\i\fs24\lang2057  Nation}{\fs24\lang2057 
 that Mr Keino arrived at Parliament Buildings at 1 pm and proceeded to his office where he packed his bags assisted by a <foreign/>commissionaire. <#/>He then drove away to present himself at the KNA offices at Nyayo House at 2. 15 pm.
\par <#/>He told the KNA reporter that he was relieved to see him and inquired whether a photo-copier machine was available. <#/>There was none and the reporter therefore copied Mr Keino's letter of resignation. <#/>Mr Keino then signed the copy.
\par <#/>However, he declined to answer any questions from the reporter, saying only that he should go by what he had by way of the brief letter of resignation.
\par <#/>Mr Keino's last official function was on Friday when he led the Freedom From Hunger Council pre-walk procession through Nairobi's streets which was flagged off by the Deputy Chairman of the Nairobi City Commission, Mrs Jane Kiano. <X_>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>Mr Keino is the chairman of the hunger council.
\par <#/>As House Speaker, Mr Keino presided over a Parliament (the sixth since independence) that has incr
easingly come under severe criticism from the public and Press for its inept and low level of debate and an increasing violation of the House's Standing Orders.
\par <#/>In his ceremonial wig and ermine gown, the Speaker has real powers in Parliament and, like a judge in a court of law, he is treated with great deference. <#/>His word in the House is generally law.
\par <#/>This is the second time Mr Keino has made an exit from the powerful and imposing position of controlling the deliberations of the August House and as a symbol of dignity of Parliament.
\par <#/>In 1983 he was the Deputy House Speaker when Members sought to discuss a religious meeting at Rungiri in Kiambu which had called for prayers for Mr Charles Njonjo, a former powerful Minister for Constitutional Af
fairs then the subject of a judicial inquiry.
\par <#/>Mr Keino, then the MP for Kericho East (since renamed Kipkelion), ruled out debate on the issue. <#/>The House was in uproar and he resigned when an MP moved a vote of no confidence in him as Deputy Speaker.
\par <#/>He was to be dubbed a collaborator in the highly publicised Njonjo affair which was fraught with charges of misconduct and of a plot to seize power through devious means.
\par <#/>In the snap election that came in the wake of the Njonjo fall-out, Mr Keino lost his Parliamentary seat. <#/>Then he was kicked out of Kanu.
\par <#/>In a surprise turn of events, and at a time when his name was rarely heard of, Mr Keino made a dramatic come-back in April, 1988 to be elected unopposed as Speaker of Kenya's sixth Parliament, thus ending the 17-year reign of Mr Mati.
\par <#/>Mr Keino's exit from the exalted position of House Speaker comes in the wake of accusations levelled against him by senior leaders in Kericho District that he was attempting to interfere in the forthcoming by-election in Kipkelion.
\par <#/>At the beginning of last month, it was alleged that Mr Keino was out to block the candidature of Mr Wilson Koske, his immediate successor to the constituency's leadership when he fell from grace in 1983.
\par <#/>What seemed to lend weight to the accusations against Mr Keino was that they were led by the Minister for Public Works, Mr Timothy Mibei, at a major Kanu recruitment drive in the district's capital of Kericho.
\par }\pard\plain \s46\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v <#/>It was also not lost on observers that present at the Ker
icho rally were prominent leaders from neighbouring Nandi District, such as nominated MP Mr Ezekiel Barng'etuny and the MP-elect for Mosop, Mr Stephen Kositany.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The accusations were taken up by a galaxy of district leaders, who, while not naming names,
 charged that a senior leader from the district was holding night meetings on the pretext that he was on a Government mission}{\fs24\lang2057 .</X>
