\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <I> <h> <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Cabinet reshuffled}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 President Daniel arap Moi yesterday announced a mini-cabinet reshuffle in which he switched two ministers, elevated an assistant minister, and promoted a member of parliament.
\par <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 
The mini-reshuffle was necessitated by the recent mysterious death of the Minister for Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation, the late Dr Robert John Ouko, and the sacking of a Minister of State in the Office of the President, Mr Johnstone Mwendo 
Makau, on March 2.
\par <#/>Mr Wilson Ndolo Ayah, the Minister for Water Development until yesterday, had been transferred to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation to replace the late Ouko.
\par <#/>His place has been taken by Mr John Okwanyo, who has been the Minister for Regional Development.
\par <#/>Mr Mathews Onyango Midika, who has been an Assistant Minister for Labour, was elevated to a full ministerial position and becomes the new Minister for Regional Development.
\par <#/>The MP for Machakos Town, Mr John Kyalo, was promoted to become a Minister of State in the Office of the President and replaces Mr Makau.
\par <#/>Mr Ayah, 56, was born at Kitambo in West Seme location of Kisumu district about 20 miles from Kisumu town. <#/>After primary education, 
he did his "O" level examination at Maseno High School from where he proceeded to Makerere University, Uganda, to pursue a Bachelor of Arts degree in Economics, History and Mathematics.
\par <#/>From 1959 to 1961, he attended Wisconsin University, USA, where he obtained a Masters degree in Agricultural Economics.
\par <#/>In 1987 he was appointed to a full cabinet post as the Minister for Research, Science and Technology, replacing Mr Odongo Omamo.
\par <#/>Mr Mathew Onyango Charles Midika was born on August 19, 1937. <#/>He received his early education in Kenya. <#/>He attended Makerere University between 1962 and 1965 where he graduated with a degree in political science.
\par <#/>He was <-/fisrt> elected MP for Nyando constituency in 1974 and was re-elected during the 1979 general elections.
\par <#/>During the 1988 elections, Mr Midika managed to capture the Muhoroni seat. <#/>He was then appointed an Assistant Minister for Labour, a position he held until his present appointment as a minister.
\par <#/>Mr Okwanyo was born in South Nyanza in 1928 and received his early education at Kisii High School between 1946 and 1950 before joining the Medical Training Centre (MTC), Nairobi, where he qualified as a radiographer in 1953.
\par <#/>Mr Okwanyo was first elected to Parliament in 1969 to represent Migori.
\par <#/>He was appointed an Assistant Minister for Foreign affairs in 1969 and then a Minister for Industry in 1979 before moving to head the Ministry of Energy from 1980 to 1982.
\par <#/>Mr John Kyalo was born in Machakos in 1931 and attended Kabaa Intermediate School and Tororo High School in Uganda where he passed his school certificate in 1951.
\par <#/>In 1952 he won a government of India cultural scholarship and studied at New Delhi University until 1957 obtaining a Bachelor of arts degree in history and a Master of arts degree in political science.
\par <#/>Mr Kyalo contested Machakos Town parliamentary seat in 1983 but failed and again in 1988 when he trounced his sole rival, Mr John Mwanzia Kikuyu.
